data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

EF Core 11 **removes the sync-over-async opt-in** for the Cosmos DB provider entirely. The configuration you used in .NET 10 (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()` — and `SaveChanges()` will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the Cosmos provider only supports async I/O.

## Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, renamed with `Async` suffix
- All EF operations use their `*Async` counterparts
- Callers up the chain must also be updated to `await`

The `Add()` call stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory. The actual I/O happens in `SaveChangesAsync()`.
